These tests verify two critical correctness properties of a rules engine:

**First-reject-wins test:**
```rust
#[test]
fn test_multiple_rules_first_reject_wins() {
    let mut engine = RulesEngine::new();
    engine.load(r#"
rule "no-rm" { on tool:bash  reject matches(command, "rm")  reason "No rm" }
rule "no-sudo" { on tool:bash  reject matches(command, "sudo")  reason "No sudo" }
"#).unwrap();

    let mut ctx = EvalContext::new(RuleEvent::Tool("bash".to_string()));
    ctx.set_str("command", "sudo rm -rf /");
    let result = engine.evaluate(&ctx, None);
    assert!(matches!(result, RuleAction::Reject(_)));
}
```

**Why:** Without this test, the engine might: (a) only check the last rule, (b) return Allow because rules conflict, or (c) panic on multiple matches. The test proves deterministic behavior: any reject wins.

**Unless-override test:**
```rust
#[test]
fn test_unless_overrides_reject() {
    engine.load(r#"
rule "block-rm" {
  on tool:bash
  reject matches(command, "rm")
  unless confirmed_by_user
  reason "rm needs confirmation"
}
"#).unwrap();

    // Without confirmation -> reject
    let result = engine.evaluate(&ctx, None);
    assert!(matches!(result, RuleAction::Reject(_)));

    // With confirmation -> allow (unless overrides reject)
    ctx2.set_bool("confirmed_by_user", true);
    let result2 = engine.evaluate(&ctx2, None);
    assert!(matches!(result2, RuleAction::Allow));
}
```

**Why:** The `unless` clause is the escape hatch that lets users override safety rules after explicit confirmation. Testing both states (with/without the override) proves that: (a) the rule blocks by default, (b) the override actually works, and (c) the override doesn't accidentally disable all rules. This is the two-stage pattern: test the defense, then test the authorized bypass.

